title: Women in costume, ca. 1915
Morris D. Tacher, restaurant owner, December 4, 1949
description: Transcribed from photograph: "[Photo caption] Specialties simmer in their exotic sauces on the stove at Morris Tacher's restaurant. Seasoning is a vital part of Tacher's cooking and meals present many unusual vegetables and other foods. [Obituary] Morris D. Tacher, 78, of 4726 50th Av. S., Seattle restaurant owner and operator 29 years, died today of cancer in a hospital. Born in Celevria, Turkey, Mr. Tacher came to Seattle from there in 1913. He owned, and, until his illness, operated the Turkish Restaurant in the Pike Place Market. Mr. Tacher was a retired member of Local 104, Boilermaker's Union; a member of the Seattle Sephardic Brotherhood and Sephardic Bikur Cholim Synagogue. Surviving are his wife, Selda, three sons, David and Jack Tacher, both of Seattle, and Sol Tacher, Bellevue; two daughters, Mrs. Ay Oziel, Seattle, and Mrs. Mike Cordova, Bellevue, and 18 grandchildren. Funeral services will be at 1 o'clock tomorrow at the Seattle Jewish Chapel, with burial in Bikur Cholim. The family suggests remembrances to the Cancer Fund." The photograph appeared in a Seattle Times article on Tacher on December 4, 1949. Tacher passed away July 8, 1965. According to the 1948/1949 City Directory, the restaurant was located at 87 Pike St., stall 9.

title: Class of Walla Walla School, June 6, 1911

description: Transcribed from duplicate photograph description: "Public Library. 1906-1957. Interior: office of Librarian's secretary (Miss Effie Chapman was secretary from Feb 23, 1909-Oct 1, 1943)."

title: Librarians at desk in Seattle Central Library Children's Room, ca. 1911
description: Alice Mills Walter appears on the left and Winnifred Washburn appears on the right. The Children's Room was located in the Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber and opened in 1906.

title: Periodical Department at Seattle Central Library, ca. 1910
description: The Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber, opened in 1906. Vincent H. Gowen (department assistant) appears on the left and Marion D. Thum (department head) appears on the right.

title: Fremont Branch Interior, Seattle Public Library, ca. 1905
description: Photograph featured on page 13 of the Library's 1905 Annual Report. The Fremont Branch was housed in two locations prior to the construction of the Carnegie library in 1921. Between 1903 and 1912, the library was located at 3424 1/2 Fremont Ave N. on the SW corner of N. 35th St. and Fremont Ave. N. Between 1913 and 1920, the branch was located at 3425 Fremont Avenue N. on the SE corner of N. 35th St. and Fremont Ave. N.
subjects: Seattle Public Library. Fremont Library Branch

title: Judson Toll Jennings in Seattle Central Library office, ca. 1910
description: No information accompanies photograph but the man at the desk is believed to be Judson Toll Jennings who served as city librarian starting in 1907. A photograph of his secretary, Effie Chapman's, similar office in the Carnegie Central Library can be seen in spl_shp_40956.

title: Seattle buses during transit strike, January 13, 1946
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SE 783826 ... New York Bureau. Transit system strike hits Seattle. Seattle's only public transit system rolled to a stop causing a reported 50% business slump, cut in school attendance, and added slow-up for returning veterans. Some 150 buses are shown in one of the idle yards. Credit line (ACME). 1-13-46 (SA) NY #4" The Seattle City Directory lists one of the Seattle Transit Company locations at 1333 Airport Way S, Seattle, WA 98134. This appears to be the most likely location for the photograph given the appearance of Smith Tower in the background.

title: Pacific Fisherman, Inc., ca. 1975
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Boats and boat building are familiar sights in Ballard." The 1975 city directory lists the company at 5351 24th Ave NW.

title: Reference Room in temporary Seattle Central Library, ca. 1905
description: Photograph featured on page 19 of the Library's 1905 Annual Report. After fire destroyed the Library's Yesler Mansion home on the evening of December 31, 1900, the library moved into temporary quarters in the Old Territorial University Building at 4th Ave. and University St. The University had recently moved to its new campus and the building was vacant.

title: Seattle Central Library at 4th Ave. and Spring St., ca. 1906
description: The Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber, opened in 1906. This photograph shows the library before the 4th Avenue Regrade (1907-1909) which would lower the street and require the library to construct a larger staircase leading to the front entrance.

title: Men attempting to rescue bus passengers following accident, April 11, 1946
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SE 1196... (Seattle Bureau). Bus Tragedy. Seattle, Wash. -- Rescuers hack their way thru the top of a North Coast Bus in an attempt to save its 19 passengers shortly after it collided with an oil truck and careened into the Duwamish River south of Seattle (4/7). Nine persons are dead from the accident which parallels that of the Spokane, Washington, baseball team in Snoqualmie Pass last summer. Photo Courtesy Washington State Patrol by E.W. Kenyon, Jr. 64. Credit Line (ACME Photo)."
photographer: Washington State PatrolKenyon, E.W., Jr.Acme Newspictures

title: Rowe Machine Works, ca. 1975
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Photo of the rear of the Rowe Machine Works on the Ballard waterfront. Fred Rowe started his business in 1911 at a site across the tracks from the present structure."

title: Men reading in Seattle Central Library Newspaper Room, ca. 1910

title: Seattle Central Library clipping and postcard, ca. 1907
description: The Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber, opened in 1906. The clipping (published December 5, 1907 in the Seattle Post-Intelligencer) shows the proposed library entryway, necessitated by the 4th Avenue Regrade (1907-1909) which lowered the street significantly. The postcard shows the stairway after construction was completed.

title: Colonial Theatre, 1916
description: Colonial Theatre showing "Fires of Conscience" with W.M. Farnum, originally released in 1916. The Nanking Cafe appears to the left.

title: Seattle Central Library Bindery, 1910

title: Charlotte Wallace, Superintendent of Circulation in her office at Seattle Central Library, ca. 1910
description: Charlotte Elizabeth Wallace served as the Superintendent of Circulation starting in 1909 according to the Library's Annual Reports. The photo shows her in her office at the Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber and opened in 1906.

title: Seattle Central Library Bindery, 1910
description: The Bindery was located in the Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber and opened in 1906. William A. Fisher, who appears at the left, is listed as a department assistant in the 1910 annual report.

title: Ballard Transfer Company van, ca. 1975
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Many things in Ballard remind us of her past. This is a Ballard Transfer & Storage Co. truck that is still in use." The 1975 city directory lists the company at 2417 NW Market St.

title: Washington State Patrol at the scene of a bus accident, April 11, 1946
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SE 1197... (Seattle Bureau). Bus Tragedy. Seattle, Wash. -- Washington State Patrol officers emerge from North Coast Lines bus after removing the nine dead from the ill-fated vehicle. The bus, shown here after being towed to higher ground, collided with an oil truck and plunged into the Duwamish River carrying 19 Seattle-bound passengers. Photo courtesy Washington State Patrol by E.W. Kenyon, Jr. 64. Credit Line (ACME Photo)." The April 8, 1946 Seattle Times article ""Stage Careens into Duwamish after Collision"" notes that the location of the accident was near the Pacific Highway (now referred to as Highway 99) and S. 104th St.
photographer: Washington State PatrolKenyon, E.W., Jr.Acme Newspictures

title: Children's Room in temporary Seattle Central Library, ca. 1905
description: Location is presumed to be in the Old Territorial University Building at 4th Ave. and University St. (See photograph spl_shp_40961 to see a similar room identified at the University Building in the Library's 1905 annual report.) After fire destroyed the Library's Yesler Mansion home on the evening of December 31, 1900, the library moved into temporary quarters in the Old Territorial University Building. The University had recently moved to its new campus and the building was vacant.

title: Ballard machine shop, ca. 1975
description: Transcribed from photograph: "This is a photograph of a machine shop on the Ballard waterfront. Ballard originated as an industrial area and much of Ballard's waterfront is still utilized by industry."

title: Fremont Baptist Church, ca. 1975

description: The Children's Room was located in the Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber and opened in 1906. The monthly calendar at the desk shows that July 1 falls on a Saturday which occurred in 1911 and 1916.

title: Seattle Central Library reference stacks, 1940
description: The Carnegie Central Library, designed by P.J. Weber, opened in 1906. By the 1940s, the library was experiencing severe space and structural issues. It was demolished in 1957 and replaced with a larger midcentury building.

title: Line outside liquor store preparing for V-J Day celebrations, August 12, 1945
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA768--New York Bureau. Stocking up for V-J Day. Seattle, Wash. -- A long line of customers waits outside a Seattle liquor store to purchase "fuel" for V-J Day celebrations. Inside of state store is filled with over 200 customers. Little boy at right, center, is just looking on -- he's not in line. NY S&S NWK. Credit (ACME). 8/12/45 (MD)."
